Dashboard Required UI Elements
•(V)	Navigation bar with logo, links to Equipment, Customers, Rentals, and API Docs
•(V)	4 KPI cards: Total Equipment Items, Available Equipment, Active Rentals, Total Customers
•(V)	A table of the 5 most recent rentals (latest first) showing: rental ID, customer name, equipment name, dates, status badge (color-coded)
•(V)	A quick-action bar with buttons: Add Equipment, New Rental, Register Customer

Equipment List Required UI Elements
•(V)	Table listing all equipment: ID, Name, Category, Daily Rate, Qty, Available status
•(V)	A search/filter bar at the top (filter by category using a dropdown + filter by name using a text input)
•(V)	Action buttons per row: View Details, Edit, Delete (with a JS confirm dialog)
•(V)	A prominent 'Add New Equipment' button at the top right
•(V)	Pagination (5 items per page)  OR  a client-side JavaScript filter

Equipment Detail Required UI Elements
•(V)	Full equipment card: name, category, description, daily rate, total qty, currently available qty
•(V)	Rental history table for this equipment item: customer name, dates, status, total cost
•(V)	Edit and Back buttons

Add / Edit Equipment  Required UI Elements
•(V) 	Form fields: Name (text), Category (select with predefined + 'Other' option), Description (textarea), Daily Rate (number, min $1), Quantity (number, min 1), Available (checkbox)
•(V)	Submit button label changes based on mode: 'Add Equipment' vs 'Save Changes'
•(V)	Cancel button links back to the equipment list
•	Server-side validation: all fields required; rate and quantity must be positive numbers
•	On validation failure, re-render the form with field-level error messages and preserve user input (no data loss on error)

Customer List Required UI Elements 
•(V)	Table: ID, Name, Email, Phone, Registered Date, Actions (Edit, Delete)
•(V)	Search by name or email (text input)
•(V)	'Register Customer' button

Customer Registration Required UI Elements 
•(V)	Fields: Full Name, Email, Phone, (created_at auto-set server-side)
•	Email uniqueness validation: reject duplicate emails with a clear error message

Rentals List Required UI Elements
•(V)	Table: Rental ID, Customer Name, Equipment Name, Start Date, End Date, Status (badge), Total Cost
•	Filter by status dropdown (All / Active / Returned / Overdue)
•(V)	A 'Mark as Returned' button on Active rows

Rentals New Required UI Elements
•(V)	Customer dropdown (populated from all customers)
•(XV)	Equipment dropdown (populated from available equipment only — available=True AND quantity > active rentals)
•(XV)	Start Date, End Date (date pickers; end must be after start)
•(XV)	Auto-compute and display Total Cost when both dates are selected (daily_rate * number of days)
•	Validation: no double-booking — same equipment cannot be rented twice in an overlapping period

Reports Required UI Elements
•	Revenue summary: total revenue (sum of all returned rental costs), active rental revenue (sum of active)
•	Top 3 most-rented equipment items (by number of rentals)
•	Top 3 customers by total spend
•	Rentals by status: a simple visual bar (CSS width % based on count vs total)



5.1  Template Inheritance (Mandatory)
Every HTML page must extend base.html using the block/extends pattern. base.html must define the following named blocks:
•	{% block title %} — used to set the <title> tag per page
•	{% block nav_active_* %} — used to highlight the active navigation item
•	{% block content %} — the main page body
•	{% block scripts %} — optional per-page JavaScript


5.2  Other Required Jinja2 Features
Feature	Where It Must Appear
{% for %} loop	Equipment list, customer list, rental list, KPI dashboard
{% if %} / {% elif %} / {% else %}	Status badge coloring, form edit/create mode, empty-state messages
{{ variable }}	Every template that displays data
{{ variable | filter }}	At least 2 Jinja filters used (e.g. |upper, |round(2), |length, |default)
{% with messages %} flash()	Success and error flash messages on form submissions
{% include %} or Jinja macro	At least one reusable component (e.g. status badge macro)
url_for()	All href links and form actions use url_for — no hard-coded URLs


7.2  Code Style
•(V)	Follow PEP 8: 4-space indentation, max 79 chars per line, snake_case naming
•(V)	No commented-out debug code in the final submission
•(V)	Flask debug mode must be set via environment variable, not hard-coded True in app.py
•(V)	Use Flask Blueprints — all routes must be registered via blueprints, not directly on the app object

7.3  Error Handling
•(V)	Register custom error handlers for 404 (Not Found) and 500 (Internal Server Error)
•(V)	API endpoints must never return an HTML error page — they must always return JSON
•	Wrap database write operations in try/except; return HTTP 422 or 400 with a JSON error body on failure